\section{Why \code{sd} and \code{n} are dropped on the model rows}{

The do-files build the model rows from \verb{mat A = r(table)'}, whose first eight
columns are \verb{b, se, t, p, ll, ul, df, crit}. They are then given the column
names \verb{Beta SE Tv Pv Min Max SD N}. So on a \verb{Trend_*} / \code{CATDif} / \code{TrendDif}
row the \code{SD} column actually holds the \strong{degrees of freedom} and \code{N} holds
the \strong{critical value} -- which is why those rows show \code{N = 1.959964}
throughout the sheets. Mapping them to \code{sd} and \code{n} would silently pass off a
z-value as a sample size, so this function sets both to \code{NA} there and keeps
them only on the \code{tabstat}-derived mean rows, where they mean what they say.
}

\section{Trend flavor}{

Engine B's trend is not the same estimator in every study, and the sheet does
not record which was used (see \code{descriptive_indicator_shares()}). Pass
\code{trend_statistic = "trend_pct"} for a \verb{margins ... eydx} semi-elasticity
(resource_extraction) or \code{"change_pp"} for a wave difference in percentage
points (land_tenure). Getting it wrong mislabels percent as percentage points.
}

